26. Reduction to a Fredholm equation

By the results of 24, the inverse problem reduces to the solution of the system (24.31)(24.35). First, rewrite equation (24.31) as

$$\begin{align*} \mu -\mathbf{1}& =C_{w,x}[\mu -\mathbf{1}]+\cdots +C_{w,x}[\mathbf{1}]+\cdots \\ & = \mathrm{Operator} [\mu -\mathbf{1}]+r, \end{align*}$$

where $r$ is the following vector function.

26.2$$\begin{align} r_{x}(z)& \equiv (C_{w,x}[\mathbf{1}])(z)+\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mathbf{1}v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},z)\cssId{texmlid286}{\tag{26.2}}\\ & =\ (C_{-}[\mathbf{1}w_{x}^{+}P(\cdot , z)])(z)\\ & +\ (C_{+}[\mathbf{1}w_{x}^{-}P(\cdot , z)])(z)+\sum _{j}(z-z_{j})^{-1}\mathbf{1}v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j,\,z}) \end{align}$$ for $z\in \Sigma \backslash 0$, and

26.3 $$\begin{align} r_{x}(z_{k})& =\int _{\Sigma }(\zeta -z_{k})^{-1}\mathbf{1}w_{x}(\zeta )P(\zeta ,z_{k})\frac{d_{\zeta }}{2\pi i}\cssId{texmlid314}{\tag{26.3}}\\ &\quad +\sum _{j\neq k}(z_{k}-z_{j})^{-1}\mathbf{1}v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j}, z_{k}) \end{align}$$

for $z_{k}\in Z$.

In terms of $r_{x}$, equations (24.31) and (24.32) for $\mu (x, \cdot )$ take the form

26.4 $$\begin{equation} h=C_{x}h+r_{x}=C_{x}h+C_{x}\mathbf{1} \cssId{texmlid246}{\tag{26.4}} \end{equation}$$

for a function $h=\mu (x, \cdot )-\mathbf{1}:(\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup Z\rightarrow \mathbf{C}^{n}$, where

$$\begin{align} C_{x}h &=(C_{x}h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0},C_{x}h|_{Z})\tag{26.5}\\ &\equiv \left((C_{w, x}h)(\cdot )+\sum _{j}(\cdot -z_{j})^{-1}h(z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},\cdot ),\right.\\ &\quad \left.\int _{\sum }(\zeta , -\cdot )^{-1}h(\zeta )w_{x}(\zeta )P(\zeta , \cdot )\frac{d_{\zeta }}{2\pi i}+\sum _{z_{j}\neq }(\cdot -z_{j})^{-1}h(z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},\cdot )\right), \end{align}$$

or symbolically,

26.6 $$\begin{align} &C_{x}h =(C_{x}h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0},C_{x}h|_{Z})\cssId{texmlid540}{\tag{26.6}}\\ &=(h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0}, h|_{Z}) \left(\begin{array}{cc} C_{w,x}[\cdot ] & \int _{\Sigma }(\zeta -\cdot )^{-1}[\cdot ]w_{x}(\zeta )P(\zeta , \cdot )\frac{d_{\zeta }}{2{\pi i}}\\\sum _{j}(\cdot -z_{j})^{-1}[\cdot ]v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},\cdot ) & \sum _{z_{j}\neq .}(\cdot -z_{j})^{-1}[\cdot ]v_{x}(z_{j})P(z_{j},\cdot ) \end{array}\right). \end{align}$$

We would like to solve equation (26.4) for $h$ in the space $Y_{N}$ for any $N$, where

26.7 $$\begin{align} Y_{N}=\{h:(\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup &Z\rightarrow \mathbf{C}^{n}:h(\alpha z)=h(z)\quad \mathrm{for}\ z\in (\Sigma \backslash 0)\cup Z\cssId{texmlid289}{\tag{26.7}}\\ &\mathrm{and\ the\ restriction\ of}\ h\ \mathrm{to}\ \Sigma \backslash 0\ \mathrm{lies\ in}\ H^{N}(\Sigma )\} \end{align}$$

26.8$$\begin{equation} |h|=\Vert h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0}\Vert _{{H^{N}}(\Sigma )}+ \sum _{j}\Vert h(z_{j})\Vert \quad \mathrm{for}\ h\in Y_{N}. \cssId{texmlid248}{\tag{26.8}} \end{equation}$$ It is not clear, however, that $C_{x}$ maps $Y_{N}$ to $Y_{N}$ unless $w$ belongs to the ideal

26.9 $$\begin{equation} H_{0}^{N}(\Sigma ; M_{n}(\mathbf{C}))\subset H^{N}(\Sigma ;M_{n}(\mathbf{C})), \cssId{texmlid541}{\tag{26.9}} \end{equation}$$

which consists of those functions vanishing to order at least $N-1$ at the origin on each ray. If $w$ also has small norm, then (as we show later) the operator

$$\begin{equation*} \left(\begin{array}{cc} C_{w,x}[\cdot ] & 0\\0 & 0 \end{array}\right) \end{equation*}$$

maps $Y_{N}$ to $Y_{N}\cdot$ with small norm. In addition (see below), $C_{X}$ is a compact perturbation of this operator, so we can conclude that (26.4) is a Fredholm equation of index zero. We devote the remainder of this section to showing how the inversion problem can be reduced to a similar one where $w$ has small norm and belongs to $H_{0}^{N}(\Sigma )$. Note that if $w$ belongs to $H_{0}^{N}(\Sigma )$ and $h$ solves (26.4), then (24.33) is automatic for $\mu \neq 1+h$; in fact, the sum vanishes to order $N-1$.

For convenience we introduce the notation

26.10 $$\begin{equation} \Vert h\Vert _{N}\equiv \Vert h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0}\Vert _{{H^{N}}(\Sigma )}. \cssId{texmlid542}{\tag{26.10}} \end{equation}$$

Thus (26.8) becomes

$$\begin{equation*} |h|=\Vert h\Vert _{N}+\sum _{j}\Vert h(z_{j})\Vert . \end{equation*}$$

We also use

26.11 $$\begin{equation} \rho (z)=\sqrt {1+|z|^{2}}. \cssId{texmlid543}{\tag{26.11}} \end{equation}$$

In the sequel we will be interested in the situation where $N$ and $K$ are large numbers, $N\gg n$ and $K\gg n$. Note also that, by the proof of Lemma 26.13, we can always assume that

(26.47) the poles of $X(z)$ in any $\Omega _{k}$ are simple and distinct from $Z$, and no two entries have a common pole.

We look for a normalized eigenfunction for $S_{x}$ in the form

26.48 $$\begin{equation} \mu (x, z)=\mu ^{\#}(x,z)X_{x}(z) \cssId{texmlid277}{\tag{26.48}} \end{equation}$$

where

26.49 $$\begin{equation} X_{x}(z)=e^{ixzJ_{-}(z)}X(z)e^{-ixzJ_{-}(z)}. \cssId{texmlid556}{\tag{26.49}} \end{equation}$$

The function $\mu ^{\#}(x, z)$ has poles on a finite set $Z^{\#}\subset \mathbf{C}\backslash \Sigma$,

26.50 $$\begin{equation} \alpha Z^{\#}=Z^{\#}, \cssId{texmlid557}{\tag{26.50}} \end{equation}$$

consisting of the disjoint union of $Z$ and the poles of $X$.

Suppose $z_{j}\in Z$. Near $z_{j}$,

26.51 $$\begin{equation} \mu (x,z)=\frac{\mu (x,z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}+\mu (x, z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|) \cssId{texmlid558}{\tag{26.51}} \end{equation}$$

and

26.52 $$\begin{equation} X(z)=(I+\lambda (z_{j})(z-z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|)^{2})X(z_{j}) \cssId{texmlid268}{\tag{26.52}} \end{equation}$$

where $\lambda (z_{j})$ is strictly upper triangular, or

$$\begin{equation*} (26.52)'\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad X_{x}(z)=(I+\lambda _{x}(z_{j})(z-z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|)^{2})X_{x}(z_{j}), \end{equation*}$$

where

26.53 $$\begin{equation} \lambda _{x}(z_{j})=e^{ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}\lambda (z_{j})e^{-ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}. \cssId{texmlid559}{\tag{26.53}} \end{equation}$$

Thus

26.54 $$\begin{align} \displaystyle \mu ^{\#}(x,z)&=\frac{\mu (x,z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}\cssId{texmlid270}{\tag{26.54}}\\ &\quad +\,\mu (x, z_{j})(X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})-v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})\lambda _{x}(z_{j}))+O(|z-z_{j}|). \end{align}$$

Set

26.55 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(z_{j})\equiv (I-X(z_{j})v(z_{j})X^{-1}(z_{j})\lambda (z_{j}))^{-1}X(z_{j})v(z_{j})X(z_{j})^{-1}, \cssId{texmlid269}{\tag{26.55}} \end{equation}$$

26.56 $$\begin{align} v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})&=e^{ixz_{i}J(z_{i})}v^{\#}(z_{j})e^{-ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}\cssId{texmlid560}{\tag{26.56}}\\ &=(I-X_{x}(z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})\lambda _{x}(z_{j}))^{-1}X_{x}(z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j}). \end{align}$$

The properties of $v(z_{j})$, $X(z_{j})$, and $\lambda (z_{j})$ ensure that $v^{\#}(z_{j})$ (and hence $v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j}))$ exists and is strictly upper triangular. Furthermore,

26.57 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=0. \cssId{texmlid271}{\tag{26.57}} \end{equation}$$

Indeed, $v^{\#}(z_{j})$ is of the form $(I-EF)^{-1}E$ with $E^{2}=0$. But $(I-EF)^{-1}E= E(I-FE)^{-1}$ by simple algebra; hence $v^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=[(I-EF)^{-1}E][E(I-FE)^{-1}] =0$.

Finally, as $X(\alpha z)=X(z)$, it follows from (26.52) that $\lambda (\alpha z_{j})=\alpha ^{-1}\lambda (z_{j})$ and hence from (26.55) and $(20.2)_\mathrm{b}$,

26.58 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(\alpha z_{j})=\alpha v^{\#}(z_{j}),\qquad z_{j}\in Z. \cssId{texmlid273}{\tag{26.58}} \end{equation}$$

Now,

$$\begin{equation*} \mu (x, z_{j})[X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})-v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j})\lambda _{x}(z_{j})]v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})=\mu (x, z_{j})v_{x}(z_{j})X_{x}^{-1}(z_{j}), \end{equation*}$$

and it follows from (26.54) and (26.57) that

26.59 $$\begin{equation} \mathrm{Res}[\mu ^{\#}(x,\cdot );z_{j}]=\lim _{z\rightarrow z_{j}}\mu ^{\#}(x, z)v_{x}^{\#} (z_{j}). \cssId{texmlid281}{\tag{26.59}} \end{equation}$$

Suppose $z_{j}\in Z^{\#}\backslash Z$. Near $z_{j}$,

$$\begin{equation} \mu (x, z)\ =\mu (x,z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|), \tag{26.60} \end{equation}$$

26.61$$\begin{equation} X(z)=\frac{\lambda (z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}+\hat{X}(z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|), \cssId{texmlid272}{\tag{26.61}} \end{equation}$$ for suitable matrices $\lambda (z_{j})$ and $\hat{X}(z_{j})$, where $\lambda (z_{j})$ is proportional to $e_{pq}$ for some $p<q$, by (26.47), or

$$\begin{equation*} (26.61)'\qquad \qquad \qquad \qquad X_{x}(z)=\displaystyle \frac{\lambda _{x}(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}+\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j})+O(|z-z_{j}|), \end{equation*}$$

where again

26.62 $$\begin{equation} \left\{\begin{array}{l} \lambda _{x}(z_{j})=e^{ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}\lambda (z_{j})e^{-ixz_{j}J(z_{j})},\\\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j})=e^{ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}\hat{X}(z_{j})e^{-ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}. \end{array}\right. \cssId{texmlid561}{\tag{26.62}} \end{equation}$$

Set

26.63 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(z_{j})=-\lambda (z_{j})(\hat{X}(z_{j}))^{-1}, \cssId{texmlid276}{\tag{26.63}} \end{equation}$$

26.64 $$\begin{equation} v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})=e^{ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}v^{\#}(z_{j})e^{-ixz_{j}J(z_{j})}=-\lambda _{x}(z_{j})(\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j}))^{-1}. \cssId{texmlid562}{\tag{26.64}} \end{equation}$$

Again $v^{\#}(z_{j})$ (and hence $v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})$) is strictly upper triangular and

26.65 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=0. \cssId{texmlid287}{\tag{26.65}} \end{equation}$$

Indeed, $e_{pq}X^{-1}(z_{j})e_{pq}X^{-1}(z_{j})=(e_{q}, X^{-1}(z_{j})e_{p})e_{pq}X^{-1}(z_{j})=0$, as $X^{-1}(z_{j})e_{p}$ is in the span of $(e_{1}, e_{2,\ldots ,}e_{p})$ and hence is orthogonal to $e_{q}$.

Finally, from $X(\alpha z)=X(z)$ and (26.61), we conclude $\lambda (\alpha z_{j})=\alpha \lambda (z_{j})$, and hence

26.66 $$\begin{equation} v^{\#}(\alpha z_{j})=\alpha v^{\#}(z_{j}),\qquad z_{j}\in Z^{\#}\backslash Z, \cssId{texmlid563}{\tag{26.66}} \end{equation}$$

as in (26.58).

From $(26.61)'$,

$$\begin{equation*} X_{x}^{-1}(z)=(\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j}))^{-1}\left(I-\frac{v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}+O(|z-z_{j}|)\right)^{-1}, \end{equation*}$$

which, by strict upper triangularity, can be expanded out in a finite sum of terms of the form

26.67 $$\begin{equation} \left(\frac{v_{x}^\#(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}-O(|z-z_{j}|)\right)^{k}. \cssId{texmlid274}{\tag{26.67}} \end{equation}$$

As $v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})^{2}=0$, the only terms surviving in (26.67) have the form

$$\begin{equation*} \frac{1}{(z-z_{j})^{m-1}}F_{1}(z)v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})F_{2}(z)v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j}) \cdots F_{m-1}(z)v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})F_{m}(z) \end{equation*}$$

where $F_{2}(z),\ldots , F_{m-1}(z)$ are $O(|z-z_{j}|)$ as $z\rightarrow z_{j}$. It follows that $\mu ^{\#}(x, z)= \mu (x, z)X_{x}^{-1}(z)$ is of the form

$$\begin{equation*} \mu ^{\#}(x, z)=\frac{A_{x}}{z-z_{j}}+B_{x}+O(|z-z_{j}|) \end{equation*}$$

for suitable $A_{x}$ and $B_{x}$, as $z\rightarrow z_{j}$. Solving for $A_{x}$ and $B_{x}$ from

$$\begin{align*} \mu (x,z_{j})&+O(|z-z_{j}|)\\ &=\left[\frac{A_{x}}{z-z_{j}}+B_{x}+O(|z-z_{j}|)\right]\left[I-\frac{v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})}{z-z_{j}}+O(|z-z_{j}|)\right]\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j})\\ &=\frac{-A_{x}v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j})}{(z-z_{j})^{2}}+\frac{[A_{x}-B_{x}v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})]}{(z-z_{j})}\hat{X}_{x}(z_{j})+O(1), \end{align*}$$

we learn, in particular, that $A_{x}=B_{x}v_{x}^{\#} (z_{j})$; the second order pole vanishes automatically as $A_{x}v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j})=B_{x}(v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j}))^{2}=0$.

We have proved

26.68 $$\begin{equation} \mathrm{Res}[\mu ^{\#}(x, \cdot );z_{j}]=\lim _{z\rightarrow z_{j}}\mu ^{\#}(x, z)v_{x}^{\#}(z_{j}). \cssId{texmlid280}{\tag{26.68}} \end{equation}$$

Let $S^\#=(Z^{\#}, v^{\#})$, where $v^{\#}$ is defined on $(\Sigma \backslash 0)\,\cup \, Z^\#$ through (26.17), (26.55), and (26.63).

In order to construct a normalized eigenfunction $\mu (x, \cdot )$ for $S_{x}$, it is enough by Proposition26.69 to construct $\mu ^{\#}(x,\cdot )$. It remains to derive the equation for $\mu ^{\#}$.

In terms of these definitions, the equation for $h^{\#}(\cdot )=\mu ^{\#}(x, \cdot )-\mathbf{1}$ is obtained simply by setting $v_{x}\mapsto v_{x}^{\#},\ w_{x}\mapsto w_{x}^{\#}$, and $r_{x}\mapsto r_{x}^{\#}$ in (26.2)(26.5). (Note that the exact shape of $v(z_{j})$ in (20.7) is irrelevant; all that is needed in the derivation of (26.4) is $v(z_{j})^{2}=0$, which holds for $v^{\#}(z_{j})$ by (26.57) and (26.65).)

In symbols, the equation equivalent to (26.4) is

26.90 $$\begin{equation} h^{\#}=C_{x}^{\#} h^{\#}+r_{x}^{\#}. \cssId{texmlid288}{\tag{26.90}} \end{equation}$$

This is the reduction advertised at the beginning of the section.
